solutions.content:
For O(n) time complexity: Even though there is a nested loop, the number of iterations equals the length of the text. For O(1) space complexity, we can use a 26-length array for any size input string, so space is constant.

I could definitely see the follow up question being "How do we adapt this solution to match a given string other than balloon?" So I used a variable instead of a string literal, like `"balloon".split('')...`

```
var maxNumberOfBalloons = function(text) {
    // Use a variable so we can easily change the "balloon" string (or could just use a target param if given)
    const target = "balloon";

    // Edge cases 
    if (text.length < target.length) return 0;

    // Use a 26 length array to keep track of character counts
    let countByCharArr = Array(26).fill(0);

    // Load character counts into arr
    text.split('').forEach( char => countByCharArr[char.charCodeAt(0)-97]++);

    // Only iterate for the possible number of balloons based on length
    const maxTargetMatches = text.length / target.length;

    // Decrement, returning if there are no target characters left (use var so you can return the count outside of the for-loop block scope)
    for (var count = 0; count < maxTargetMatches; count++){
        if (target.split('').some( char => 0 > --countByCharArr[char.charCodeAt(0)-97])){
            return count;
        }
    }

    return count;
};
```

