# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Count Total Possible Paths using concept from unique Paths problem.
Now to find Kth Instruction-
Divide the range in the range of number of left "H" and "V" counts
Wherever k lies add that to answer

Eg-(2,3)==>Total paths=10 horizontal moves=3, Vertical moves=2;
k=4;
Dividing 1 to 10 in ratio of 3:2
First 6 paths will start with "H" and then rest with "V"
k<=6 therfore ans.append("H");
new ratio 2:2 range 1 to 6
First 3 paths will start with "H" and then rest with "V"
k>3 therfore ans.append("V");
new ration 2:1 range 4 to 6
Recursively we will find next moves by modifying range with left over moves.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n^2)$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n^2)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String kthSmallestPath(int[] d, int k) {
        int m=d[0]+1;
        int n=d[1]+1;
        int dp[][]=new int[m][n];
        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
          for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
            if(i==0 && j==0) dp[i][j]=1;
            else if(i==0)dp[i][j]=dp[i][j-1];
            else if(j==0)dp[i][j]=dp[i-1][j];
            else dp[i][j]=dp[i][j-1]+dp[i-1][j];
          }
        }
        StringBuffer sb=new StringBuffer();
        int lo=1,hi=dp[m-1][n-1];
        int h=n-1,v=m-1;
        while(h!=0 && v!=0){
          int mid=(int)(h*(((hi-lo+1)*1.0)/(h+v)));
          if(k<=mid+lo-1){
            sb.append("H");
            hi=mid+lo-1;
            h--;
          }
          else{
            sb.append("V");
            lo=mid+lo;
            v--;
          }
        }
        while(v-->0)sb.append("V");
        while(h-->0)sb.append("H");
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```

