```
/*
    Use normal Dijkstra algorithm
    -> Objective is to find number of paths leading to same destination cost
    -> conisder vertices -> u1, u2 and u3
    -> with costs for reaching there from source are as follows -> c1, c2, c3
    -> consider u1 is connected to v1 (directed or un-directed doesn't really matters)
    -> similarly u2 and u3 are also connected to v1
    -> Now let us assume there are n1 ways for reaching u1 from source
    -> similarly assuming n2 and n3 ways for reaching u2 and u3 respectively
    -> Suppose cost to reach v1 from u1 is w1 ( i.e edge cost u1---v1 )
    -> similarly cost to reach v1 from u2 & u3 are w2 and w3 respectively
    -> Assume cost to reach v1 is W
    -> if c1+w1 < W
    ->  then we update the distance ( just like classic dijkstra), but now we know that there are also n1 ways to reach u1)
    ->  i.e to reach v1 from destination there will be n1 ways only.
    ->  let this new updated weight be W1
    -> if c2+w2==W1
    ->  then we found another path with same source to v1 cost, then there will be (n2+n1) different ways to reach v1
    ->  Since for reaching v1 from u2 there are n2 ways and we already know that there are also n1 different ways to reach v1

*/
class Solution {
    int count = 0;
    int MOD = (int)(1e9+7);
    public int shortestTimeToDest(int start, int dest, int n, Map<Integer, List<int[]>> graph){
        // dijkstra
        int[] distances = new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(distances, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        int[] count = new int[n];
        // min heap
