# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
As for Dijkastra's algo require: 
1.Distance array
2.Data structure like set or Priority_queue to store distance in ascending order
3.additional requirement is that as have to store number of ways to reach destination from source will take another data structure to store it's path let take vector.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Except for maintaining the seperate array/vector for number of shortest ways every thing is similar as Dijkstra's shortest path algo.
**
So, For maintaining the seperate array/vector for number of shortest ways follow below instructions**:
1).If the no of shortest paths for particulr node is empty or we are going to add for the first time directly add the number of shortest path from the parent node.
ways[adjNode]=ways[node]
2).And if already there is already entry for shortest path for particualr node then add the number of shortest path from parent and the current number of the shortest path of the node.
** ways[adjNode]=(ways[adjNode]+ways[node])**

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Time Complexity=O(Elogn)  here E=no.of edge and n=no. of nodes in graph

- Space complexity:O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int countPaths(int n, vector<vector<int>>& roads) {
        vector<long>dist(n,LONG_MAX);
         int mod=1e9+7;
        //store undirected graph
        vector<pair<int,int>>adj[n];
        for(auto x:roads){
            int u=x[0];
            int v=x[1];
            int wt=x[2];
            adj[u].push_back({v,wt});
            adj[v].push_back({u,wt});
        }
        vector<long>path(n,0);
        priority_queue<pair<long,int>,vector<pair<long,int>>,greater<pair<long,int>>>q;
        q.push({0,0});
        dist[0]=0;
        path[0]=1;
        while(!q.empty()){
           long d=q.top().first;
             int node=q.top().second;
            q.pop();
            for(auto x:adj[node]){
                int v=x.first;
                int wt=x.second;
                //edge relaxation
                if(dist[v]>d+wt){
                    //update
                    dist[v]=d+wt;
                    q.push({dist[v],v});
                    //mark path as visited first time with it's minimum reachability
                    path[v]=path[node];
                }
                else if(d+wt==dist[v]){
                    path[v]=(path[v]+path[node])%mod;
                }
            }
        }
        return path[n-1];
    }
};
```

